							<!-- End each blog post -->
							
														
							<div class="post_wrapper author">
								<div id="about_the_author">
									<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/sheilasquillante/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/Sheila-Squillante-100x100.jpeg" width="100" height="100" alt="Sheila Squillante" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
									<div class="description author withsidebar">
										<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/sheilasquillante/">Sheila Squillante</a></h6>
										Sheila Squillante is the author of the poetry collections, <em>Mostly Human</em>, winner of the 2020 Wicked Woman Book Prize from BrickHouse Books, and <em>Beautiful Nerve</em>, as well as three chapbooks of poetry: <em>In This Dream of My Father</em>, <em>Women Who Pawn Their Jewelry</em> and <em>A Woman Traces the Shoreline</em>. She is also co-author, along with Sandra L. Faulkner, of the writing craft book, <em>Writing the Personal: Getting Your Stories Onto the Page</em>. Her nonfiction has appeared in <em>The Rumpus</em>, <em>River Teeth</em>, <em>Brevity</em>, <em>Bennington Review</em>, <em>Barrelhouse</em> and elsewhere. She directs the MFA program in creative writing at Chatham University, where she is Executive Editor of The Fourth River, a journal of nature and place-based writing. She lives in Pittsburgh, PA, with her family.																			</div>
								</div><br class="clear"/><br/>
							</div>
